<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Host Population, Development Forum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101110194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0959 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>Jan. 11</DATE> KYODO -- <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> will cosponsor an 
eminent persons' meeting on the subjects of population and 
development on <DATE>January 26</DATE> and 27 in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> 
spokesman <PERSON>Terusuke Terada</PERSON> said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> [11 <DATE>January</DATE>]. 
  The meeting will formulate its recommendations to a 
UN-sponsored conference in <LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION> next <DATE>September</DATE>. 
  Some 20 high-level scholars, academics and political leaders 
who are well-versed in the problems of population will attend 
the meeting at the <ORGANIZATION>UN University</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Terada</PERSON> said. 
  Participants will include such prominent figures as 
Norwegian 
Prime Minister <PERSON>Gro Harlem Brundtland</PERSON>, former Mexican President 
<PERSON>Miguel</PERSON> de la <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>, former <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Robert McNamara</PERSON> 
and <PERSON>Taro Nakayama</PERSON>, former Japanese foreign minister. 
  The meeting is to be held under the cosponsorship of the 
<ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> 
Population Fund (<ORGANIZATION>UNFPA</ORGANIZATION>), the <ORGANIZATION>UN University</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign 
Ministry</ORGANIZATION>. 
  Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON>Morihiro Hosokawa</PERSON> will address the 
opening ceremony. 
  The participants are expected to adopt a <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> declaration 
on 
the closing day. 
  The deliberations at the meeting will be recommended to the 
<ORGANIZATION>U.N.-sponsored International Conference on Population and 
Development</ORGANIZATION>, which is to be held in <LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION> in <DATE>September</DATE> to 
discuss measures for problems related to the rapidly increasing 
world population. 
  <PERSON>Terada</PERSON> said <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> is by far the largest donor country for 
<ORGANIZATION>UNFPA</ORGANIZATION>, donating <MONEY>59 million dollars</MONEY> in <DATE>1992</DATE> and as much as <MONEY>63 
million dollars</MONEY> in <DATE>1993</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

