<H3> <TI>   UN Population Meeting Ends With Declaration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701092894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0652 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2701092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>Jan. 27</DATE> KYODO -- A <ORGANIZATION>United Nations-sponsored</ORGANIZATION> 
meeting on population and development concluded <DATE>Thursday</DATE> [27 
<DATE>January</DATE>] with a declaration urging governments to curb 
population growth. 
  The two-day conference was held at the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations 
University</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>. 
  "Population growth is a major obstacle to the alleviation of 
poverty, sustained socioeconomic development, and the 
improvement of the status of women," said the draft text of the 
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> declaration of the meeting of eminent persons on 
population and development. 
  The meeting, also sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION>, was 
held 
in preparation for the <ORGANIZATION>International Conference on Population 
and Development</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>ICPD</ORGANIZATION>) slated for <DATE>September</DATE> in <LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION>. 
  "We...call upon all governments and intergovernmental and 
nongovernmental organizations to do their utmost to make the 
(<LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION>) conference a milestone in the global effort to eradicate 
poverty and socioeconomic inequality, to achieve sustained 
economic growth and sustainable development, to improve the 
status and role of women and to reduce population growth," it 
said. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION> has predicted the world population, now 
at 
<MONEY>5.6 billion</MONEY>, will increase to 10 billion by <DATE>2050</DATE>. 
  The declaration urged developing countries to integrate 
population issues into national development planning, and 
developed nations to change their patterns of consumption and to 
curb overproduction in order to reduce the impact on the 
environment and on the use of resources. 
  It also urged "the world community...to increase their 
financial commitment to population and related activities in 
developing countries in order to reach the estimated amount of 
approximately <MONEY>13 billion dollars</MONEY>...by the year <DATE>2000</DATE> and 
approximately <MONEY>17 billion dollars</MONEY> by the year <DATE>2015</DATE> annually." 
  At a news conference held immediately after the meeting 
ended, <ORGANIZATION>International Planned Parenthood Federation</ORGANIZATION> President 
<PERSON>Fred Sai</PERSON>, vice chairman of the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> meeting, said, "one thing 
which has come out here...is that...we have to start addressing 
population issues much more seriously." 
  He said the other point stressed through the discussion was 
the importance of "partnership between the developed and 
developing countries." 
  The news conference was also attended by <PERSON>Nafis Sadik</PERSON>, 
executive director of the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. Population Fund</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>U.N. University 
Rector Heitor Gurgulino de Souza</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Population 
Council</ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON>Maher Mahran</PERSON> [name as received] and 
former Japanese Foreign Minister <PERSON>Taro Nakayama</PERSON>, chairman of the 
gathering. 
  The 14-member panel of the meeting debated sustainable 
development, family planning and the status of women in relation 
to population. 
  The panel also included former <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Robert 
McNamara</PERSON>, former Mexican President Miguel de la <PERSON>Madrid Hurtado</PERSON> 
and former <LOCATION>Kiribati</LOCATION> President <PERSON>Jeremia T. Tabai</PERSON>. 

</TEXT>

