<DATE>Aug. 10</DATE> (<TIME>8:47 p.m. EDT</TIME> <DATE>Aug. 9</DATE>). Asian experts, however, predict the
milestone will be reached within days.
   Professor <PERSON>Gayl D. Ness</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University of Michigan</ORGANIZATION> estimated
that <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>'s population would grow to 3.5 billion by the end of the
century and to 4.5 billion by <DATE>2025</DATE>, while the world population
reaches 8.2 billion.
   Rice production will have to increase <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> by <DATE>2025</DATE> to feed
the continent, <PERSON>Ness</PERSON> said, but great gains already have been
registered by farmers in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION>.
   The 21st century targets ``are well within the realm of
possibility if the agricultural transformation continues. This, of
course, requires sensitive government policies,'' said the
sociologist and researcher on Asian population.
   <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> has made ``substantial progress'' in lowering fertility
rates, and Asian countries were the first to adopt policies to
limit population growth, he said.
   But Ness noted disparities in different regions of <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>. East
Asian countries such as <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, which has 122 million
people, have rapidly declining fertility rates.
   But in <LOCATION>South Asia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is still experiencing <PERCENT>2.08 percent</PERCENT>
annual growth in its population of 818 million; <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> has <PERCENT>3.45
percent</PERCENT> growth with 115 million people; and <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION> has <PERCENT>2.67
percent</PERCENT> growth rate from a current base of 110 million, according
to <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> figures.
   ``The challenge lies ahead in completing the demographic
transition and bringing birth rates down to match the fall in the
death rates,'' <PERSON>Ness</PERSON> said.
   He and other panelists were critical of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> for
withdrawing money from the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. Fund</ORGANIZATION> for Population Activities
because of the fund's support for abortion.
   The population growth also has caused some social changes.
   Professor <PERSON>Toshio Kuroda</PERSON>, director emeritus of <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Institute
of Population</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Nihon University</ORGANIZATION>, noted that <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> ``expects the
family to care for the aged ... but the family is undergoing
tremendous change in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> with the one-child family.''
   <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, the world's most populous country with 1.08 billion
people, has since the early <DATE>1980s</DATE> limited most families to one
child. But the limit has been widely flouted in the past two years.
   In <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION>, Chinese officials marked the Day of 3 Billion In
<LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> with a ceremony in the <PERSON>Great Hall</PERSON> of the People.
   They handed out cassette players to 18 family planning workers,
doctors and others for ``outstanding performance in implementing
our population policy.''
   Speakers warned that rapid population growth poses a threat to
economic development.
   ``We cannot think that we can have more children because of
economic development ... nor can we relax our efforts because of
progress in family planning,'' said <PERSON>Hu Keshi</PERSON>, forum vice chairman.
</TEXT>
