<H3> <TI>   Well-Being of Hokkaido's Ainu Population Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Well-Being of Hokkaido's Ainu Population Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0504113294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1038 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0504113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Sapporo</LOCATION>, <DATE>April 5</DATE> KYODO -- Most of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s minority 
Ainu remain dissatisfied with their standard of living, 
according to a survey released by the prefectural government on 
<ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s northernmost main island. The survey showed 
that <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT> of the Ainu families interviewed on <ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido</ORGANIZATION> 
said they find it "tough" to make ends meet, while another <PERCENT>44 
percent</PERCENT> opted to characterize it as "somewhat difficult." 
  A total of 300 Ainu families in <LOCATION>Hokkaido</LOCATION>, where most of 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s Ainu live, were interviewed last <DATE>June</DATE> for the survey, 
which has been conducted every seven years since <DATE>1972</DATE>. Despite 
complaints about difficulties in earning a livelihood, the 
survey showed that ratio of Ainu receiving welfare payments from 
the government fell from 60.9 per 1,000 population in the last 
survey, undertaken in <DATE>1986</DATE>, to 38.8 per 1,000 population in the 
current survey. 
  The survey said <ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido</ORGANIZATION>'s Ainu population stood at 23,830, 
or a decrease of 551 over the last survey. 
  There are few remaining full-blooded Ainu in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. Counted 
as <ORGANIZATION>Ainu</ORGANIZATION> in the survey were those thought to have at least some 
Ainu blood or those living in families with members who have 
Ainu blood. 
  The survey said the percentage of Ainu children going on to 
senior high school increased by 9 points to <PERCENT>87.4 percent</PERCENT>, though 
it fell short of the <PERCENT>96.3 percent</PERCENT> overall figure for Hokkaido 
children. A bigger gap surfaced in the figures for those 
children proceeding to university or college, with <PERCENT>11.8 percent</PERCENT> 
for the relevant Ainu population compared with <PERCENT>27.5 percent</PERCENT> for 
the overall population. 
  In a questionnaire targeting Ainu aged 15 and older, only 
<PERCENT>7.3 
percent</PERCENT> said they faced incidences of discrimination over the 
past six or seven years, while <PERCENT>62 percent</PERCENT> said they had not. 
  Officials said the <ORGANIZATION>Hokkaido Prefectural Government</ORGANIZATION> intends 
to 
use the survey in planning its future Ainu welfare policies. 

</TEXT>

