<H3> <TI>   Consumption Tax May Reappear as `Welfare Tax' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001040494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0323 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001040494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>Jan. 20</DATE> KYODO -- The consumption tax may be 
renamed the "welfare tax" in a bid to win public support for 
raising it, government sources said <DATE>Thursday</DATE> [20 <DATE>January</DATE>]. 
  The issue has been deliberated within government circles for 
some time, the sources said. 
  The governing coalition has been under pressure to clarify 
the purpose of the tax in light of the rapid aging of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 
population, they said. 
  It is also being argued that a name change could help win 
support for raising the current rate from <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT>, a move that 
is strongly opposed by the <ORGANIZATION>Social Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION> [of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>], 
the largest party in Prime Minister <PERSON>Morihiro Hosokawa</PERSON>'s 
coalition government. 
  The idea has met with criticism from some people engaged in 
various welfare programs, who fear that the amount of tax 
collected under that name might be regarded as a ceiling for 
welfare spending. 

</TEXT>

