<H3> <TI>   New Candidates Challenge Incumbent in Yokohama </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2003153494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1009 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Yokohama</LOCATION>, <DATE>March 20</DATE> KYODO -- Two new faces <DATE>Sunday</DATE> 
[20 <DATE>March</DATE>] filed as candidates to challenge the incumbent in the 
<DATE>April 3</DATE> mayoral election in <LOCATION>Yokohama</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s second most 
populous city. 
  The three men who filed candidacy papers were incumbent 
mayor 
<PERSON>Hidenobu Takahide</PERSON>, 64, and challengers <PERSON>Toshihiko Izu</PERSON>, 67, and 
<ORGANIZATION>Takashi Nomura</ORGANIZATION>, 40. 
  All three are independents. 
  <PERSON>Takahide</PERSON>, who is seeking a second four-year term of office, 
has gained the backing of the <ORGANIZATION>Liberal Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION>, the 
Social Democratic Party, <LOCATION>Komeito</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Shinseito</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Japan Renewal 
Party</ORGANIZATION>) and the Democratic Socialist Party. 
  Izu, a professor emeritus at <ORGANIZATION>Yokohama City University</ORGANIZATION>, is 
backed by the Japanese Communist Party, while <ORGANIZATION>Nomura</ORGANIZATION>, a former 
<ORGANIZATION>Home Affairs Ministry</ORGANIZATION> bureaucrat, has garnered support from new 
party Sakigake and the <ORGANIZATION>United Social Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION>. 
  <LOCATION>Yokohama</LOCATION>, the largest international port city in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, has 
a 
population of 3.3 million, ranking second after <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> which has 
a population of more than eight million. 
  The challengers have accused <PERSON>Takahide</PERSON> of having received a 
huge amount of election campaign funds from general contractors. 
Takahide denies the allegation. 

</TEXT>

