<H3> <TI>   Discusses Changes in Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Changes in Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504040994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0341 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504040994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <DATE>April 25</DATE> KYODO -- Outgoing Foreign Minister 
<PERSON>Tsutomu Hata</PERSON>, who is virtually certain to become premier later 
in the day, repeated suggestions <DATE>Monday</DATE> that he may ask Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) Chairman <PERSON>Tomiichi Murayama</PERSON> to join the 
new cabinet. 
  Hata also indicated at a press conference after an 
extraordinary cabinet meeting, where the eight-month-old cabinet 
of prime minister <PERSON>Morihiro Hosokawa</PERSON> resigned, that the changes 
in the new cabinet will be small to middle-scale. 
  Hata said that "in general," it is better to have heads of 
coalition parties in the cabinet to reflect the parties' 
opinions, indicating he may ask Murayama to join the cabinet. 
There were six <ORGANIZATION>SDP</ORGANIZATION> cabinet ministers in the <LOCATION>Hosokawa</LOCATION> government 
but <PERSON>Murayama</PERSON> did not hold any cabinet post. 
  Hata, who was also deputy premier in the <LOCATION>Hosokawa</LOCATION> 
administration, said that in principle, it is desirable for the 
ministers who helped compiled the fiscal <DATE>1994</DATE> budget bill to 
remain in the cabinet and respond to upcoming Diet 
interpellations on the budget. 
  Reviewing his eight-month-long tenure as foreign minister, 
<PERSON>Hata</PERSON> said he felt the world expected <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> to speak up more on 
the international scene. 
  <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> could make various proposals on problems such as 
population, environment, AIDS, disarmament and arms control, he 
said. 
  Hata also said foreign ministers should not change so often 
and that he regrets he was only able to hold the post for eight 
months. 
  He also said <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> should push ahead with deregulation. 

</TEXT>

