<H3> <TI>   Greenpeace Ship Arrives To Protest Reactor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greenpeace Ship Arrives To Protest Reactor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3003085694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0742 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3003085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Fukui</LOCATION>, <DATE>March 30</DATE> KYODO -- Activists of the 
international environmental organization <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> arrived 
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> [30 <DATE>March</DATE>] aboard the patrol boat MV <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> in 
<LOCATION>Tsuruga</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fukui Prefecture</LOCATION>, to protest the start-up of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s 
prototype fast breeder reactor Monju there. 
  During the 10-day port call at <LOCATION>Tsuruga</LOCATION>, Captain <PERSON>Arne 
Sorensen</PERSON> 
and 18 <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> activists will inform local residents of the 
dangers Monju poses for the environment in videos and a photo 
exhibition on the boat, spokeswoman <PERSON>Etsuko Ikeda</PERSON> said. 
  The fast breeder operated by the governmental <ORGANIZATION>Power Reactor 
and Nuclear Fuel Development Corp.</ORGANIZATION> will soon reach what is 
called "criticality," the stage when a nuclear chain reaction is 
self-sustaining. Ikeda said <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> estimates Monju will 
reach criticality on <DATE>April 8</DATE>. 
  The reactor, which uses a mixture of highly toxic plutonium 
and enriched uranium as fuel, will then produce 280,000 
kilowatts of electricity. 
  In a recent report, <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> warned that Monju "could 
explode like an atomic bomb, killing thousands and contaminating 
most population centers in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and neighboring countries." 
  <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> also alleged that the Japanese Government is 
withholding important data on the safety risk posed by Monju. 
Noting that the original safety assessment for the fast breeder 
was undertaken over 10 years ago, <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> called for a new 
safety review and a full environmental impact statement. 
  On its previous mission last <DATE>October</DATE>, the MV <ORGANIZATION>Greenpeace</ORGANIZATION> 
monitored nuclear waste dumped into the Sea of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> by <LOCATION>Russia</LOCATION> 
and the former <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>

